    tern:equipment """
    <h3 id="equipment-4">Equipment</h3>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      Mobile device (tablet/phone capable of taking high resolution photos) with
      the App<br />
      (progressive web app) saved to the home screen
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Soil corer (5 cm diameter; 10 cm increments marked on the outside)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Trowel, small shovel, auger</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Alcohol spray and small scrubbing brush</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      30 medium sized snap lock bags per plot (22 x 25 cm; white block for
      labelling)
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Large plastic bag per plot to store individual samples together (ca. 50 x
      60 cm)
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Adhesive voucher labels (with barcodes)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Permanent marker</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>10 survey pins</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Trimble® R1 (GNSS receiver with sub-metre accuracy and Bluetooth
      connectivity).
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
    """^^rdf:HTML ;
    tern:instructions """
    <h3 id="instructions-and-procedures-4">Instructions and procedures</h3>
<ol type="1">
  <li>
    <p>
      Ensure the <em>Plot selection and layout</em> module has been completed to
      mark out the plot grid with sub-metre accuracy using the Trimble® R1,
      including the 25 x 25 m soil sub-site zone in the southwest corner of the
      plot (see Figure 1).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the ‘Soils’ module and then the ‘Soil chemistry sampling’ protocol
      in the App. The App will automatically record the
      <em>Plot name</em>, based on the established plot you are working in, the
      <em>Protocol</em> and the <em>Date</em>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record who the soil chemistry samples are <em>Collected by</em> from the
      drop-down list of personnel affiliated with your user login.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record the <em>Agency</em> from the drop-down list of agencies affiliated
      with your user login.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Record the <em>State</em> from the drop-down list.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record a brief <em>Location description</em> (i.e. a general description
      to assist with plot re-location using distances and direction to
      landmarks).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select ‘Locate SW corner’ to launch the mapping interface and locate the
      southwest corner of the plot with sub-metre accuracy using the Trimble®
      R1.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select ‘Record SW corner location’. The App will automatically record the
      <em>Easting</em>, <em>Northing</em>, <em>Zone</em>, <em>Datum</em> and
      location acquisition <em>Method</em> (i.e. ‘DGPS’).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select 'Locate 10 random samples'. The App will randomly select and
      display 10 sampling locations from the 10 x 10 grid with lines spaced 2.5
      m apart (i.e. 100 potential sampling locations; see Figure 2). If it is a
      repeat survey, the App will randomly select 10 sampling locations from
      potential sampling locations that are yet to be sampled from. Sampling
      locations are randomly selected using a Latin Square approach, where each
      row and column is sampled only once in each sampling event.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Using the Trimble® R1, traverse to each sampling location. Mark each with
      a survey pin and select 'Record sampling location'. The App will
      automatically record the <em>Easting</em>, <em>Northing</em>,
      <em>Zone</em>, <em>Datum</em> and location acquisition
      <em>Method</em> (i.e. ‘DGPS’, as well as the
      <em>Sampling location</em> based on its row (A–J) and column (1–10; see
      Figure 2).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Return to each sampling location to collect the soil core. Still in the
      mapping interface, select the location you are sampling. This will
      navigate to a data entry screen for the sampling location.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Brush any loose and obvious material from the soil surface.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Ensure that the soil corer is not contaminated from another location. Use
      alcohol spray and a small scrubbing brush to clean if necessary.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Collect stacked (i.e. use the same sample hole) soil cores from each depth
      increment separately using the 10 cm marking on the outside of the soil
      corer.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Place and seal the three samples into separate zip-lock bags and label
      each with the plot code, date, sampling location, depth increment and a
      barcode.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the 'Scan 0–10 barcode' button to scan the barcode label on the
      0–10 cm sample and link the sample to the plot, survey date, sampling
      location and depth increment.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the 'Scan 10–20 barcode' button to scan the barcode label on the
      10–20 cm sample and link the sample to the plot, survey date, sampling
      location and depth increment.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the 'Scan 20–30 barcode' button to scan the barcode label on the
      20–30 cm sample and link the sample to the plot, survey date, sampling
      location and depth increment.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the 'Save sampling location' button to save the sampling location
      and return to the mapping interface to select the next sampling location.
      Collect the survey pin before moving on.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Repeat steps 11–19 for each sampling location.</p></li>
  <li><p>Record any Additional metagenomics soil sub-site comments.</p></li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Store all samples together in a large plastic bag and label this clearly
      with the plot number and date.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select ‘Complete Soil chemistry samples' to save the protocol and return
      to the <em>Soils</em> module.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
    """^^rdf:HTML ;
.

